posts.raw_content:
In September 1776, just days after the British took New York City, a young American spy was dragged before a British gallows. Nathan Hale, a 21-year-old schoolteacher-turned-soldier, had been caught behind enemy lines in civilian clothes—an offense punishable by death.

There was no trial, no mercy. As dawn broke, he stood tall, bound but unbroken. British officers sneered. One offered him a final word.

Hale didn’t beg. He didn’t curse. Instead, he spoke clearly:
**“I only regret that I have but one life to lose for my country.”**

A moment later, the rope snapped tight.
But his words echoed—through newspapers, taverns, battlefields—and helped forge a nation.
